WEBVTT

00:01.668 --> 00:04.796
<i>[fire whooshing]</i>

00:06.173 --> 00:09.218
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:09.218 --> 00:14.431
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:14.431 --> 00:16.141
‐ My name's Aaron Meliza.

00:16.141 --> 00:18.519
<i>I tend to move</i>
<i>from passion to passion.</i>

00:18.519 --> 00:20.229
I've been a machinist,
I've been a welder,

00:20.229 --> 00:21.480
I've been a gunsmith,

00:21.480 --> 00:23.899
<i>I started</i>
<i>a photography company.</i>

00:23.899 --> 00:26.443
<i>But the thing that sticks</i>
<i>with me is blades.</i>

00:26.443 --> 00:28.237
<i>There's something in my brain</i>
<i>that tells me</i>

00:28.237 --> 00:30.906
that I need to make knives.

00:30.906 --> 00:33.200
<i>‐ My name's Wayne Meligan.</i>

00:33.200 --> 00:35.827
I've eat, slept, breathed
bladesmithing, man.

00:35.827 --> 00:37.162
<i>It is full throttle.</i>

00:37.162 --> 00:38.247
<i>I burn the candle,</i>

00:38.247 --> 00:39.665
<i>I don't even burn it</i>
<i>at both ends.</i>

00:39.665 --> 00:42.543
I throw the whole candle
into the fire.

00:42.543 --> 00:43.919
♪ ♪

00:43.919 --> 00:45.254
<i>‐ My name is Mark Hemley.</i>

00:45.254 --> 00:46.713
I used to be in IT.

00:46.713 --> 00:48.966
I was actually a tech
professional for about 15 years.

00:48.966 --> 00:51.885
<i>And four years ago, I decided</i>
<i>to become a blacksmith.</i>

00:51.885 --> 00:55.889
Winning would show me
that I am on the right path.

00:55.889 --> 00:57.516
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:57.516 --> 00:59.059
‐ I'm Jesse Hemphill.

00:59.059 --> 01:00.769
I'm 58 years old.

01:00.769 --> 01:03.605
<i>Winning this would just</i>
<i>mean the world to me.</i>

01:03.605 --> 01:04.731
I just got married.

01:04.731 --> 01:06.149
I wanna take
some of that money

01:06.149 --> 01:07.442
<i>and go on a honeymoon,</i>

01:07.442 --> 01:09.611
which, this is
my honeymoon right now,

01:09.611 --> 01:11.780
only she's away somewhere else,
and I'm here.

01:11.780 --> 01:14.283
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:14.283 --> 01:16.118
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:16.118 --> 01:18.328
You're here to engage
in three rounds

01:18.328 --> 01:19.955
of timed edged‐weapon‐making
competition,

01:19.955 --> 01:22.457
specifically designed to test
every aspect of your skills

01:22.457 --> 01:24.209
in front of a panel
of expert judges,

01:24.209 --> 01:25.794
that will tell us
which of you is our next

01:25.794 --> 01:27.671
"Forged in Fire" champion,

01:27.671 --> 01:31.300
walking out of here
with a check for $10,000.

01:31.300 --> 01:34.511
Up first,
ABS Mastersmith J. Neilson.

01:34.511 --> 01:37.306
Historic weapons recreation
specialist, David Baker.

01:37.306 --> 01:40.726
And last, Kali martial artist
Doug Marcaida.

01:40.726 --> 01:43.395
In this first round
of competition today,

01:43.395 --> 01:46.606
you'll be making one of these.

01:46.606 --> 01:49.026
Competition choppers.
‐ All right.

01:49.026 --> 01:52.863
‐ Now, we didn't feel that
that was complicated enough,

01:52.863 --> 01:54.114
so to ramp it up a little bit,

01:54.114 --> 01:55.407
we've got a special
surprise for you

01:55.407 --> 01:57.993
underneath that cloth
on your anvils.

01:57.993 --> 02:00.787
Go ahead and lift that cloth up.

02:00.787 --> 02:03.623
What you're looking at there
are stacks of 10‐series

02:03.623 --> 02:05.584
and 15N20 steel.

02:05.584 --> 02:09.421
<i>You will have to do a stacked</i>
<i>Damascus chopper for us,</i>

02:09.421 --> 02:13.383
<i>that is between</i>
<i>10 and 13 inches in length.</i>

02:13.383 --> 02:15.177
One other thing:

02:15.177 --> 02:16.845
You'll be doing this today.

02:16.845 --> 02:18.597
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:18.597 --> 02:21.350
Gentlemen, in an order
chosen at random,

02:21.350 --> 02:24.936
you must choose the type
of patterned Damascus

02:24.936 --> 02:28.148
that you will make
your chopper out of.

02:28.148 --> 02:29.358
Choose wisely.

02:29.358 --> 02:31.860
Not only must you stack
your steel for Damascus,

02:31.860 --> 02:34.112
but you must follow
specific steps,

02:34.112 --> 02:37.366
in order to get
each distinct pattern.

02:37.366 --> 02:38.617
<i>‐ Yikes.</i>

02:38.617 --> 02:40.077
<i>I've done a bit</i>
<i>of forge welding,</i>

02:40.077 --> 02:41.620
<i>but I haven't had much</i>
<i>experience</i>

02:41.620 --> 02:42.913
<i>with different patterns.</i>

02:42.913 --> 02:45.582
I've been a monosteel bladesmith
for most of my time,

02:45.582 --> 02:49.753
so having to make a pattern
is gonna be a bit challenging.

02:49.753 --> 02:51.922
‐ Aaron, you're up first.

02:51.922 --> 02:53.882
Come and choose your pattern.

02:53.882 --> 02:55.300
<i>‐ There are six patterns,</i>

02:55.300 --> 02:57.052
and I'm not familiar
with all of them,

02:57.052 --> 03:00.681
<i>so the stress</i>
<i>starts to kick in.</i>

03:00.681 --> 03:02.391
I select the twist pattern.

03:02.391 --> 03:04.059
<i>I'm choosing twist Damascus,</i>

03:04.059 --> 03:06.937
<i>because it's one weld</i>
<i>drawn out into a bar.</i>

03:06.937 --> 03:09.606
Twist it up, make your knife.
Seems simple.

03:09.606 --> 03:12.651
We'll see how simple it is.
[laughs]

03:12.651 --> 03:14.194
‐ All right, Mark, you're up.

03:14.194 --> 03:16.571
‐ The only two patterns I know
are twist and raindrop.

03:16.571 --> 03:18.907
<i>And luckily,</i>
<i>there's still raindrop.</i>

03:18.907 --> 03:22.411
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:22.411 --> 03:24.204
‐ All right, Jesse, you're up.

03:24.204 --> 03:29.418
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:29.418 --> 03:32.295
‐ I'm choosing
a shark's tooth pattern.

03:32.295 --> 03:34.339
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:34.339 --> 03:37.008
‐ All right, Wayne,
come and choose your pattern.

03:37.008 --> 03:39.803
<i>‐ So, being the</i>
<i>last smith to go,</i>

03:39.803 --> 03:41.304
it pretty much sucks,

03:41.304 --> 03:43.265
<i>because I'm getting</i>
<i>the leftover scraps</i>

03:43.265 --> 03:45.058
<i>that no one else</i>
<i>wanted to get,</i>

03:45.058 --> 03:47.769
<i>and usually that's because</i>
<i>it's a more difficult pattern.</i>

03:47.769 --> 03:49.938
I believe I'll take
ladder pattern.

03:49.938 --> 03:51.606
‐ All right.

03:51.606 --> 03:53.275
<i>‐ But I see</i>
<i>my good old friend,</i>

03:53.275 --> 03:54.818
<i>Mr. Ladder Damascus.</i>

03:54.818 --> 03:57.112
<i>I have made</i>
<i>ladder Damascus before.</i>

03:57.112 --> 03:58.280
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:58.280 --> 04:00.782
‐ Bladesmiths, you'll have
three hours in this round

04:00.782 --> 04:02.451
in which to forge your blades.

04:02.451 --> 04:04.703
Now, in the second round, you'll
attach handles to those blades

04:04.703 --> 04:06.204
to turn them into
fully functional weapons,

04:06.204 --> 04:08.123
that will be tested
for strength and durability

04:08.123 --> 04:10.959
in a copper pipe chop,

04:10.959 --> 04:14.212
and for edge retention
in a melon slice.

04:14.212 --> 04:15.964
Good luck, bladesmiths.

04:15.964 --> 04:17.841
Your three hours starts now.

04:17.841 --> 04:19.342
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:19.342 --> 04:21.136
There are just so many
different obstacles

04:21.136 --> 04:22.971
in this first round.

04:22.971 --> 04:24.264
One, you gotta make a chopper;

04:24.264 --> 04:27.142
two, you gotta make it out
of the steel that we chose;

04:27.142 --> 04:29.436
and then three, it has to be

04:29.436 --> 04:31.897
one of the patterns
that they chose.

04:31.897 --> 04:34.941
‐ No matter what pattern
they choose to make out there,

04:34.941 --> 04:37.152
the main thing is, we are
specifically looking for

04:37.152 --> 04:39.529
a look that matches
what they chose.

04:39.529 --> 04:41.656
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:41.656 --> 04:43.825
<i>‐ I want to focus on cleaning</i>

04:43.825 --> 04:45.952
<i>each and every one</i>
<i>of those pieces.</i>

04:45.952 --> 04:47.788
If you screw up
on the forge weld,

04:47.788 --> 04:49.998
it doesn't matter what you make,
it's gonna be a delamination,

04:49.998 --> 04:52.417
and shoot yourself in the foot
right from the get‐go.

04:52.417 --> 04:55.796
<i>Ladder patterned Damascus,</i>
<i>you cut up the billet,</i>

04:55.796 --> 04:58.840
<i>alternating, and almost</i>
<i>like in a ladder fashion,</i>

04:58.840 --> 05:00.634
<i>and then, whenever you</i>
<i>stretch the billet out,</i>

05:00.634 --> 05:02.135
<i>you're revealing</i>
<i>all those layers</i>

05:02.135 --> 05:03.428
<i>that you cut down into.</i>

05:03.428 --> 05:06.223
‐ Are all these patterns
able to come out

05:06.223 --> 05:07.849
with low layer counts?

05:07.849 --> 05:09.851
‐ The ladder pattern,
not too low.

05:09.851 --> 05:11.478
Twist is probably
the one you can do

05:11.478 --> 05:12.729
the lowest layer count on.

05:12.729 --> 05:15.357
The raindrop, basically
the same as ladder.

05:15.357 --> 05:16.942
And the shark's tooth,

05:16.942 --> 05:18.485
you wanna have a good
amount of layers on that.

05:18.485 --> 05:20.111
<i>‐ To get</i>
<i>a true ladder pattern,</i>

05:20.111 --> 05:22.113
you need to be at least
around 60 layers or more.

05:22.113 --> 05:24.324
<i>I just feel like</i>
<i>I don't have time to do that</i>

05:24.324 --> 05:25.659
with the three hours given.

05:25.659 --> 05:27.994
I figured it was safer
to go lower layer.

05:27.994 --> 05:29.454
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:29.454 --> 05:32.040
‐ Mark chose the
raindrop Damascus.

05:32.040 --> 05:33.542
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:33.542 --> 05:36.044
<i>‐ I know the basics</i>
<i>of the raindrop pattern.</i>

05:36.044 --> 05:38.171
<i>I know that I have</i>
<i>to forge weld the billet,</i>

05:38.171 --> 05:40.674
<i>drill holes in it, and then</i>
<i>I have to forge it some more.</i>

05:40.674 --> 05:42.050
<i>But the specific details,</i>

05:42.050 --> 05:44.928
I am kinda shooting
in the dark here.

05:44.928 --> 05:46.930
You gotta be kidding me.

05:46.930 --> 05:49.391
This is a lot to do
in three hours.

05:49.391 --> 05:52.102
<i>If it was just</i>
<i>one piece of steel,</i>

05:52.102 --> 05:53.562
<i>make a blade, no problem,</i>

05:53.562 --> 05:55.397
but having to get
the billet welded together,

05:55.397 --> 05:58.233
<i>get the pattern in there,</i>
<i>it seems daunting.</i>

05:58.233 --> 06:00.569
This is crazy!

06:00.569 --> 06:02.320
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:02.320 --> 06:05.782
<i>‐ Aaron has chosen</i>
<i>the twist patterned Damascus.</i>

06:05.782 --> 06:07.033
What do you think, J.?

06:07.033 --> 06:08.827
‐ Twist is a good call.

06:08.827 --> 06:10.036
<i>The one thing</i>
<i>you wanna make sure is,</i>

06:10.036 --> 06:11.872
<i>you form down your billet</i>

06:11.872 --> 06:13.665
<i>once you get that</i>
<i>solid weld in there.</i>

06:13.665 --> 06:15.584
<i>You don't wanna leave it</i>
<i>as a square and twist it,</i>

06:15.584 --> 06:17.919
<i>and have really high peaks</i>
<i>and low valleys</i>

06:17.919 --> 06:19.296
you gotta fight with.

06:19.296 --> 06:23.008
‐ So, this flux keeps
the steel from oxidizing,

06:23.008 --> 06:26.553
because if the steel oxidizes,
the material won't weld.

06:26.553 --> 06:27.971
I didn't buy this flux,

06:27.971 --> 06:30.724
so I get to use
as much of it as I want.

06:30.724 --> 06:33.727
[laughs]

06:33.727 --> 06:37.147
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:37.147 --> 06:40.275
‐ I've chosen
a shark tooth pattern.

06:40.275 --> 06:43.445
‐ Now, how does he create
the shark's tooth pattern

06:43.445 --> 06:45.030
in that billet of steel?

06:45.030 --> 06:46.990
<i>‐ He'll forge it</i>
<i>into a square bar,</i>

06:46.990 --> 06:50.744
<i>and actually start cutting</i>
<i>V‐shaped notches out of it,</i>

06:50.744 --> 06:52.287
<i>so it actually looks</i>
<i>like an accordion,</i>

06:52.287 --> 06:54.039
<i>and then you open that up,</i>

06:54.039 --> 06:57.500
so the flat ends brings
that pattern to the surface.

06:57.500 --> 06:59.002
‐ Got you.

06:59.002 --> 07:01.087
<i>‐ It's a bit difficult,</i>
<i>it's tricky,</i>

07:01.087 --> 07:02.422
but it looks cool as heck.

07:02.422 --> 07:05.800
It's a good, strong pattern.
I think I'm gonna nail it.

07:05.800 --> 07:09.137
‐ Bladesmiths!
One hour has elapsed!

07:09.137 --> 07:10.513
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:10.513 --> 07:14.309
‐ The key to success is
getting these welds to stick.

07:14.309 --> 07:15.602
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:15.602 --> 07:16.978
[bleep].

07:16.978 --> 07:20.982
The top layer is just
kinda, like, sliding off,

07:20.982 --> 07:24.277
like it's a piece of
melty cheese on a hamburger.

07:24.277 --> 07:26.446
‐ A lot of this is
set up in heat.

07:26.446 --> 07:29.157
Get everything tight
with that first weld.

07:29.157 --> 07:31.326
Get it hot enough
to weld together.

07:31.326 --> 07:33.453
‐ When in doubt, more flux.

07:33.453 --> 07:35.205
<i>Hit it harder.</i>

07:35.205 --> 07:37.832
<i>I don't have time</i>
<i>for this kinda problem.</i>

07:37.832 --> 07:39.209
The clock is ticking.

07:39.209 --> 07:40.835
<i>I'm hoping to set</i>
<i>the forge welds,</i>

07:40.835 --> 07:43.171
so that I can start drilling
my pattern into it.

07:43.171 --> 07:45.465
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:45.465 --> 07:47.008
‐ I've got my billet drawn out

07:47.008 --> 07:49.177
to a little bit
bigger than an inch,

07:49.177 --> 07:51.096
<i>and it's time to put</i>
<i>a twist on this.</i>

07:51.096 --> 07:52.597
‐ It's a brick right now.

07:52.597 --> 07:54.849
‐ Yeah, he's not gonna be able
to twist that, is he now?

07:54.849 --> 07:57.227
‐ It's gotta get
quite a bit thinner.

07:57.227 --> 07:58.812
‐ [pants]

07:58.812 --> 08:00.438
This billet is not moving.

08:00.438 --> 08:02.982
‐ The entire vise is moving,

08:02.982 --> 08:05.819
as Aaron tries
to twist this billet.

08:05.819 --> 08:05.860
[grunting]
<i>I'm fighting this material,</i>

08:08.446 --> 08:11.324
‐ That's the tough thing
about a twist, man.

08:11.324 --> 08:13.868
‐ Come hell or high water,
I'm getting this twist in.

08:13.868 --> 08:15.203
It's gonna happen.

08:15.203 --> 08:16.621
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:16.621 --> 08:19.374
‐ Well, now you gotta get it
horizontal this time.

08:19.374 --> 08:21.876
‐ [grunts]

08:21.876 --> 08:23.169
It starts to move.

08:23.169 --> 08:24.629
That's the way!

08:24.629 --> 08:27.132
In the back of my mind,
I'm concerned about time.

08:27.132 --> 08:30.343
<i>I was hoping to put</i>
<i>a lot more twist into it.</i>

08:30.343 --> 08:32.762
I'm just gonna have
to go with what I got.

08:32.762 --> 08:36.558
‐ Bladesmiths! You have
just 90 minutes remaining!

08:36.558 --> 08:38.476
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:38.476 --> 08:41.229
‐ I start
to manipulate the steel,

08:41.229 --> 08:44.023
and to bring about
what I'm hoping ultimately

08:44.023 --> 08:46.860
will be the pattern
that I'm looking for.

08:46.860 --> 08:50.321
I use the squaring dies,
because they have peaks on them.

08:50.321 --> 08:51.698
<i>So, what I'm actually doing is</i>

08:51.698 --> 08:55.410
squeezing down
into the steel these lines.

08:55.410 --> 08:56.911
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:56.911 --> 08:59.330
‐ You think Jesse's gonna
go for a fold on that?

08:59.330 --> 09:00.915
‐ I would love to see
a fold on that.

09:00.915 --> 09:02.542
I don't know what
he's gonna do otherwise.

09:02.542 --> 09:04.335
You definitely can't accordion
cut something like that.

09:04.335 --> 09:05.879
‐ That was my worry...
‐ It needs to be a square.

09:05.879 --> 09:07.756
‐ It's so thin, yeah.
‐ Yeah.

09:07.756 --> 09:09.257
‐ He needs a thicker billet

09:09.257 --> 09:11.468
in order to cut deep enough
V‐shaped notches,

09:11.468 --> 09:14.095
otherwise he won't get
that shark tooth pattern.

09:14.095 --> 09:15.722
Yeah, definitely one
of those challenges

09:15.722 --> 09:18.266
to follow the recipe and
follow it really closely.

09:18.266 --> 09:20.018
Really easy to screw up
one of those steps,

09:20.018 --> 09:22.395
and wind up with a pattern
that doesn't match.

09:22.395 --> 09:24.439
[blades whirring]

09:24.439 --> 09:26.775
‐ All of the forge welds
look fantastic.

09:26.775 --> 09:28.443
<i>I took my time</i>
<i>cleaning the steel,</i>

09:28.443 --> 09:30.945
but I've still got so much
more left to do on this blade.

09:30.945 --> 09:33.740
<i>I need to start cutting</i>
<i>the grooves up the billet</i>

09:33.740 --> 09:35.200
<i>for the ladder pattern.</i>

09:35.200 --> 09:37.035
<i>‐ I would've liked</i>
<i>to have seen Wayne</i>

09:37.035 --> 09:39.537
actually forge
his blade to shape

09:39.537 --> 09:41.122
before patterning it.

09:41.122 --> 09:44.876
That steel is not
10 to 13 inches long, yet...

09:44.876 --> 09:46.336
‐ Right.

09:46.336 --> 09:47.629
‐ So he's still gotta
a lot of drawing out to do,

09:47.629 --> 09:48.838
and he can wash things out.

09:48.838 --> 09:50.465
You want those nice
and tight and even.

09:50.465 --> 09:52.008
<i>‐ People, you know,</i>
<i>they see me a lot,</i>

09:52.008 --> 09:53.468
<i>doing a lot of crazy things.</i>

09:53.468 --> 09:55.220
<i>It's just my personality, man.</i>

09:55.220 --> 09:57.305
<i>I'm just all over the place,</i>
<i>taking full advantage of life,</i>

09:57.305 --> 10:01.684
whether it's in bladesmithing
or anything else that I do.

10:01.684 --> 10:03.394
Air guitar!

10:03.394 --> 10:04.938
Right there.

10:04.938 --> 10:07.107
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:07.107 --> 10:09.109
‐ I've never made
raindrop before,

10:09.109 --> 10:11.528
<i>and I'm guessing</i>
<i>that drilling the holes</i>

10:11.528 --> 10:13.780
at about half an inch
should be okay.

10:13.780 --> 10:15.281
‐ What you're doing is,

10:15.281 --> 10:17.408
you're bringing the bottom
of that drill hole

10:17.408 --> 10:20.120
back up to the surface,
so you get those rings.

10:20.120 --> 10:21.162
‐ Okay.

10:21.162 --> 10:23.873
And then, as they
draw those holes out,

10:23.873 --> 10:26.459
they should get that tapered
raindrop look, right?

10:26.459 --> 10:27.627
‐ Right.

10:27.627 --> 10:30.171
<i>‐ I want to make sure that</i>
<i>I'm doing this properly,</i>

10:30.171 --> 10:32.423
so I do a test etch.

10:32.423 --> 10:35.468
‐ It's good to see Mark
take his blade

10:35.468 --> 10:36.761
and starts etching now,

10:36.761 --> 10:38.346
so that he can see
if he would be able

10:38.346 --> 10:39.806
to accomplish that pattern.
‐ Right.

10:39.806 --> 10:43.351
‐ Not big, but I got a lot of
little bitty raindrops there.

10:43.351 --> 10:44.686
I'm gonna add more raindrops.

10:44.686 --> 10:47.188
<i>I don't think</i>
<i>this is bold enough</i>

10:47.188 --> 10:48.731
to get me through to round two.

10:48.731 --> 10:51.860
‐ Maybe it's a chance of
raindrop pattern Damascus.

10:51.860 --> 10:53.736
[laughter]

10:53.736 --> 10:55.029
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:55.029 --> 10:56.406
<i>‐ Now that I've twisted this,</i>

10:56.406 --> 10:57.991
I have all these weird
peaks and valleys,

10:57.991 --> 11:01.870
and I need to flatten it
into what resembles a blade.

11:01.870 --> 11:03.580
‐ Aaron is starting
to work his profile,

11:03.580 --> 11:06.666
but right now, he's got a billet
that's going like this,

11:06.666 --> 11:08.960
because he had that twist,
that real lazy twist

11:08.960 --> 11:10.753
that just flattened it
right out.

11:10.753 --> 11:14.757
‐ As I forge this material
into a workable chopper,

11:14.757 --> 11:18.761
I can start to see the twist
pattern appearing in the blade.

11:18.761 --> 11:22.182
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:22.182 --> 11:24.893
<i>‐ I went with a little bit</i>
<i>of a curve to the blade.</i>

11:24.893 --> 11:26.561
<i>It should be a little bit</i>
<i>forward‐heavy,</i>

11:26.561 --> 11:28.438
and it's gonna lend to chopping.

11:28.438 --> 11:30.064
<i>Everything's working out.</i>

11:30.064 --> 11:31.316
I'm actually seeing
the ladder pattern in it,

11:31.316 --> 11:32.734
<i>as I'm beating it out.</i>

11:32.734 --> 11:34.527
It still looks
like a turd, but...

11:34.527 --> 11:36.738
all beautiful blades
start out as turds.

11:36.738 --> 11:40.074
‐ Bladesmiths! You have
30 minutes remaining

11:40.074 --> 11:41.701
to finish your blades!

11:41.701 --> 11:44.829
‐ I have a chopper
with sort of a spear point

11:44.829 --> 11:47.123
<i>with a convex edge</i>
<i>for chopping.</i>

11:47.123 --> 11:48.708
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:48.708 --> 11:52.337
‐ So far, only one blade
has been quenched,

11:52.337 --> 11:55.882
but I'd really like
to see him etching.

11:55.882 --> 11:58.259
‐ No pings like it cracks.

11:58.259 --> 11:59.802
‐ There you go, all right.
‐ Yeah, there we go.

11:59.802 --> 12:01.554
‐ With a kick!
‐ That's it.

12:01.554 --> 12:04.557
‐ And I know that I have
a good quality hardness.

12:04.557 --> 12:06.226
<i>I'm ready to go.</i>

12:06.226 --> 12:07.936
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:07.936 --> 12:09.520
<i>‐ No matter</i>
<i>how thick and chunky</i>

12:09.520 --> 12:12.982
and unrefined this blade is,
it needs to be hardened.

12:12.982 --> 12:14.567
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:14.567 --> 12:17.528
‐ And Aaron's in the quench.

12:17.528 --> 12:19.197
<i>‐ It's staying</i>
<i>rather straight.</i>

12:19.197 --> 12:21.658
‐ It's a big chopper, man.
It's got a great shape to it.

12:21.658 --> 12:22.784
‐ Yeah, it does.

12:22.784 --> 12:24.369
<i>‐ The clock is still ticking,</i>

12:24.369 --> 12:26.246
<i>and I still haven't met</i>
<i>all of my parameters.</i>

12:26.246 --> 12:28.998
I need to grind
enough mill scale

12:28.998 --> 12:30.792
off of the size of the blade
to reveal the pattern,

12:30.792 --> 12:34.003
and I also need to etch it
to make the pattern visible.

12:34.003 --> 12:35.380
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:35.380 --> 12:37.507
‐ 15 minutes!

12:37.507 --> 12:39.175
<i>‐ I'm just</i>
<i>running out of time.</i>

12:39.175 --> 12:41.135
I've gotta get to heat treat.

12:41.135 --> 12:43.763
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:43.763 --> 12:46.391
It sounds good.
I pull it out.

12:46.391 --> 12:48.643
<i>That sucker starts</i>
<i>to warp on me.</i>

12:48.643 --> 12:51.145
I think I may have quenched
my blade a little too hot.

12:51.145 --> 12:52.021
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:52.021 --> 12:53.606
‐ It always makes me nervous

12:53.606 --> 12:56.484
when a smith starts twerking
the blade after quenching.

12:56.484 --> 12:58.319
<i>‐ It's straighter,</i>

12:58.319 --> 12:59.946
with a lot of emphasis
on the "er."

12:59.946 --> 13:01.406
<i>And it's hard.</i>

13:01.406 --> 13:03.199
I'm ready to hit the grinder.

13:03.199 --> 13:08.496
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:08.496 --> 13:10.832
‐ Mark just quenched his blade.

13:10.832 --> 13:12.417
<i>‐ I hit hard steel.</i>

13:12.417 --> 13:14.252
Thank goodness.
One quench.

13:14.252 --> 13:16.129
I'm on track
to get done on time.

13:16.129 --> 13:19.007
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:19.007 --> 13:21.509
‐ I know that I've got just
a little bit of time left,

13:21.509 --> 13:24.262
and I start creating my pattern.

13:24.262 --> 13:26.055
<i>It's going to be good.</i>

13:26.055 --> 13:30.018
The pattern is just not
what I had in mind.

13:30.018 --> 13:32.687
‐ I'm not sure if that's
a shark tooth pattern.

13:32.687 --> 13:35.690
The other three patterns
that the smiths are doing

13:35.690 --> 13:37.442
are pretty easy to identify.

13:37.442 --> 13:40.153
This one you're gonna have
to take a close look at.

13:40.153 --> 13:43.823
‐ I really can't come back
and cut or press anymore,

13:43.823 --> 13:46.367
so I'm gonna run with it.

13:46.367 --> 13:48.036
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:48.036 --> 13:51.539
‐ Five, four, three,

13:51.539 --> 13:53.207
two, one.

13:53.207 --> 13:54.625
Bladesmiths,
stop what you're doing!

13:54.625 --> 13:56.586
Shut down your machines!
Drop your tools!

13:56.586 --> 13:59.422
This first round of competition
is over.

13:59.422 --> 14:01.257
‐ Whoo!

14:01.257 --> 14:03.718
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:03.718 --> 14:06.012
‐ At this point, it may
not be as good as I want,

14:06.012 --> 14:08.723
<i>but I'm past the point</i>
<i>of no return.</i>

14:08.723 --> 14:09.974
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:09.974 --> 14:11.559
It's up to the judges.

14:11.559 --> 14:15.063
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:15.063 --> 14:16.856
‐ Bladesmiths, that was
a hell of a first round.

14:16.856 --> 14:18.149
Now it's time for the judges

14:18.149 --> 14:20.109
to take a closer look
at your work.

14:20.109 --> 14:21.736
Aaron, you're up first.

14:21.736 --> 14:24.030
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:24.030 --> 14:26.032
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:26.032 --> 14:27.408
<i>‐ This is heavy.</i>

14:27.408 --> 14:29.410
If you move forward,
a lot of this needs to go away

14:29.410 --> 14:31.120
to make this
a functional weapon.

14:31.120 --> 14:32.580
I can see the pattern here,

14:32.580 --> 14:35.041
<i>and the twist sort of</i>
<i>runs through it this way.</i>

14:35.041 --> 14:36.876
What often happens if you
don't twist them tight is,

14:36.876 --> 14:41.047
as you stretch them out,
that twist sort of goes away.

14:41.047 --> 14:43.758
But it is there.
Your profile is fantastic.

14:43.758 --> 14:45.760
That's a great chopper.
‐ Thank you.

14:45.760 --> 14:48.805
‐ Wayne, please present
your steel to the judges.

14:48.805 --> 14:50.932
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:50.932 --> 14:53.768
<i>‐ You still got a bit</i>
<i>of a warp in there.</i>

14:53.768 --> 14:56.270
<i>There's definitely ways</i>
<i>of correcting it.</i>

14:56.270 --> 14:58.815
You do have
a ladder pattern in here.

14:58.815 --> 15:02.527
It's not exactly a ladder
I'd be willing to try and climb,

15:02.527 --> 15:04.445
as the rungs are
kind of far apart,

15:04.445 --> 15:05.905
but it is in there.

15:05.905 --> 15:07.698
Good job.
‐ Thank you.

15:07.698 --> 15:10.743
‐ Mark, please present
your blade to the judges.

15:10.743 --> 15:13.079
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:13.079 --> 15:15.998
<i>‐ You got the pattern.</i>
<i>I see it there.</i>

15:15.998 --> 15:17.750
<i>As you refine this blade,</i>

15:17.750 --> 15:19.627
I would be very careful,
if you move forward,

15:19.627 --> 15:21.295
not to get rid of all of that.

15:21.295 --> 15:24.423
You know, already this has got
a pretty nice weight to it,

15:24.423 --> 15:27.051
but to me, that's like
a steak knife handle

15:27.051 --> 15:28.302
on a butcher knife.

15:28.302 --> 15:29.428
There's not a lot there.

15:29.428 --> 15:31.806
But, uh, you definitely
got a knife,

15:31.806 --> 15:33.141
and it looks pretty solid.

15:33.141 --> 15:34.308
Good job.

15:34.308 --> 15:35.309
‐ All right, Jesse,

15:35.309 --> 15:37.353
please present your blade
to the judges.

15:37.353 --> 15:40.022
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:40.022 --> 15:42.150
<i>‐ All right, Jesse,</i>
<i>you can forge out there.</i>

15:42.150 --> 15:43.151
<i>Good job.</i>

15:43.151 --> 15:44.318
But my concern is,

15:44.318 --> 15:46.821
it looks nothing like
what the sample was.

15:46.821 --> 15:48.531
<i>I see these wiggly</i>
<i>lines on here,</i>

15:48.531 --> 15:50.950
<i>but not that specific of</i>
<i>a shark's teeth pattern.</i>

15:50.950 --> 15:53.327
<i>We saw earlier that</i>
<i>your billet was too thin,</i>

15:53.327 --> 15:55.663
and you didn't cut those
deep V‐shaped notches

15:55.663 --> 15:58.499
that truly define
and bring out this pattern.

15:58.499 --> 16:00.293
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:00.293 --> 16:03.254
‐ Wayne, Mark, congratulations,
you guys are safe.

16:03.254 --> 16:05.965
You're moving into this
next round of competition.

16:05.965 --> 16:09.760
Aaron, Jesse, this decision
came down to your blades.

16:09.760 --> 16:10.970
J.?

16:10.970 --> 16:13.181
‐ Aaron, you gave us
a twist blade.

16:13.181 --> 16:15.683
It's a lazy twist,
but it is there.

16:15.683 --> 16:18.144
My big concern is
the weight of that blade.

16:18.144 --> 16:19.645
It's got a great profile,

16:19.645 --> 16:20.813
but there's a ton
of steel there,

16:20.813 --> 16:22.190
and that's a serious
issue for me.

16:22.190 --> 16:23.649
On the other hand, Jesse,

16:23.649 --> 16:25.985
that pattern you were going
to put in that blade,

16:25.985 --> 16:27.361
we're just not seeing it.

16:27.361 --> 16:30.031
It's not the same as the
example or close to it,

16:30.031 --> 16:32.575
so that's why we're
gonna let you go.

16:32.575 --> 16:34.452
‐ Jesse, I'm gonna
have to ask you

16:34.452 --> 16:36.370
to please surrender your weapon.

16:36.370 --> 16:37.705
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:37.705 --> 16:39.540
‐ Jesse, thank you
for coming out.

16:39.540 --> 16:41.042
<i>‐ It was a pattern challenge,</i>

16:41.042 --> 16:43.377
and, unfortunately,

16:43.377 --> 16:46.589
my pattern didn't step up.

16:46.589 --> 16:49.967
<i>The first thing I'm gonna do</i>
<i>is kiss my lovely new bride,</i>

16:49.967 --> 16:52.386
<i>and then I'm going</i>
<i>back to work.</i>

16:52.386 --> 16:54.597
I made an awesome blade.
I know I did.

16:54.597 --> 16:56.515
<i>It was a great experience.</i>

16:56.515 --> 16:59.060
So, yeah, I'm gonna
leave here smiling.

16:59.060 --> 17:01.896
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:01.896 --> 17:03.773
‐ Bladesmiths, congratulations,

17:03.773 --> 17:05.691
you've made it into the second
round of this competition.

17:05.691 --> 17:07.401
And now that those blades
have been tempered,

17:07.401 --> 17:09.320
it's time to turn them into
fully functional weapons,

17:09.320 --> 17:10.947
by attaching handles to them.

17:10.947 --> 17:14.033
You will have only two hours
to fix the flaws and issues

17:14.033 --> 17:15.576
identified in your blades.

17:15.576 --> 17:17.411
<i>You will also have to</i>
<i>finish the handles,</i>

17:17.411 --> 17:20.873
add a mosaic pin,
and a lanyard hole.

17:20.873 --> 17:22.208
After this round,

17:22.208 --> 17:24.669
your blades will be tested
for strength and durability

17:24.669 --> 17:26.295
in a copper pipe chop,

17:26.295 --> 17:29.632
and for edge retention
in a melon slice.

17:29.632 --> 17:32.927
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your two hours starts now.

17:32.927 --> 17:34.053
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:34.053 --> 17:36.222
J., tell us a little bit
about mosaic pins.

17:36.222 --> 17:38.599
‐ Basically,
it's just a hollow tube,

17:38.599 --> 17:40.935
build with other
materials and shapes

17:40.935 --> 17:43.271
to make certain patterns.

17:43.271 --> 17:44.730
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:44.730 --> 17:47.316
‐ My first game plan is
to get that mosaic pin going.

17:47.316 --> 17:49.777
<i>I found this‐‐it looks</i>
<i>like a stainless one,</i>

17:49.777 --> 17:51.237
and I'm gonna fill it
with copper,

17:51.237 --> 17:52.446
<i>so it'll contrast well.</i>

17:52.446 --> 17:53.906
‐ First thing they want
to take care of,

17:53.906 --> 17:55.366
mosaic pin, get it
out of the way.

17:55.366 --> 17:58.244
‐ Get that glued up and sat
and not have to worry about it.

17:58.244 --> 17:59.954
‐ Oh, got it.

17:59.954 --> 18:02.206
<i>I've never done</i>
<i>a mosaic pin before.</i>

18:02.206 --> 18:03.624
I understand the concept.

18:03.624 --> 18:05.835
We'll see how it goes
in execution.

18:05.835 --> 18:08.963
My favorite method
of applying epoxy

18:08.963 --> 18:10.131
<i>is finger painting,</i>

18:10.131 --> 18:12.300
so let's get dirty.

18:12.300 --> 18:15.303
‐ Mark looks more like
he's greasing bearings

18:15.303 --> 18:17.638
than actually making
a mosaic pin.

18:17.638 --> 18:19.140
‐ He's gotta cure up quick.

18:19.140 --> 18:21.642
‐ Let's call that a mosaic pin.

18:21.642 --> 18:23.394
<i>‐ The very first thing</i>
<i>I need to do</i>

18:23.394 --> 18:25.855
<i>is start hogging off material.</i>

18:25.855 --> 18:28.107
<i>That means I'm gonna be</i>
<i>generating a lot of heat</i>

18:28.107 --> 18:29.400
in my material.

18:29.400 --> 18:31.902
‐ Aaron's got a mountain
of steel to grind.

18:31.902 --> 18:33.362
It is massive.

18:33.362 --> 18:35.948
<i>‐ Introducing all of</i>
<i>this heat into the blade</i>

18:35.948 --> 18:37.408
<i>is bad for the hardness.</i>

18:37.408 --> 18:40.453
‐ Part that concerns me is,
Aaron's beating that blade.

18:40.453 --> 18:42.538
‐ Yeah, and he might
lose a little temper

18:42.538 --> 18:44.165
on that blade edge.

18:44.165 --> 18:45.374
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:45.374 --> 18:46.959
‐ Hopefully I don't overheat it.

18:46.959 --> 18:48.919
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:48.919 --> 18:51.339
<i>‐ Bladesmiths!</i>

18:51.339 --> 18:52.965
One hour has elapsed!

18:52.965 --> 18:54.884
<i>‐ So, J. told me I've got</i>
<i>a warp in this blade</i>

18:54.884 --> 18:56.344
that I've gotta get out.

18:56.344 --> 18:58.054
I want it to be
straight as possible.

18:58.054 --> 19:00.389
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:00.389 --> 19:02.016
<i>I've got my blade</i>
<i>straightened up.</i>

19:02.016 --> 19:04.268
Now it's time to make it
J. Neilson‐proof.

19:04.268 --> 19:06.312
<i>I'm gonna help soften</i>
<i>that spine down,</i>

19:06.312 --> 19:07.980
<i>and put it through</i>
<i>an extra little temper.</i>

19:07.980 --> 19:11.317
‐ Wayne, he's trying to
blue‐back that, I'm guessing.

19:11.317 --> 19:12.735
‐ Not a bad idea,

19:12.735 --> 19:14.111
you know, especially
on a chopper.

19:14.111 --> 19:17.823
That soft spine acts
as a shock absorber, striking.

19:17.823 --> 19:19.367
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:19.367 --> 19:21.285
<i>‐ The judges said that</i>
<i>the handle is a little short,</i>

19:21.285 --> 19:22.912
so I've gotta fix it.

19:22.912 --> 19:24.288
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:24.288 --> 19:26.540
‐ He's pushing the ricasso
forward on the grinder,

19:26.540 --> 19:28.292
so he's opening
that handle up more,

19:28.292 --> 19:29.919
which is exactly
what we all asked for.

19:29.919 --> 19:31.087
‐ Yeah.

19:31.087 --> 19:32.922
‐ Now it's time to put
a handle on it.

19:32.922 --> 19:34.799
Wood is what I use.

19:34.799 --> 19:37.718
I feel like I'm in
a really good spot.

19:37.718 --> 19:40.388
‐ Mark's ahead of the curve.
‐ Yeah.

19:40.388 --> 19:42.056
‐ Come on.
Yes.

19:42.056 --> 19:44.725
<i>‐ So, the key is to make</i>
<i>the nicest mosaic pin</i>

19:44.725 --> 19:46.227
in the shortest amount
of time possible.

19:46.227 --> 19:49.063
<i>I grab a little piece</i>
<i>of aluminum tubing,</i>

19:49.063 --> 19:51.357
a piece of stainless rod,
a piece of copper rod,

19:51.357 --> 19:52.608
and a piece of brass rod.

19:52.608 --> 19:53.943
<i>Then just stuff 'em</i>
<i>in the pin,</i>

19:53.943 --> 19:56.070
<i>and fill it up with</i>
<i>some blue pigmented epoxy,</i>

19:56.070 --> 19:58.698
<i>and hopefully this cures</i>
<i>as fast as I need it to cure.</i>

19:58.698 --> 20:00.241
[bleep].

20:00.241 --> 20:02.952
Okay. Cure.

20:02.952 --> 20:04.495
<i>‐ I'm sharpening my blade,</i>

20:04.495 --> 20:05.955
<i>and I'm constantly</i>
<i>checking the edge,</i>

20:05.955 --> 20:08.916
making sure that
it's going the right way.

20:08.916 --> 20:10.209
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:10.209 --> 20:14.714
‐ I'm worried about
the thickness of Mark's edge.

20:14.714 --> 20:16.716
Going into a copper pipe chop,

20:16.716 --> 20:20.594
it's got a very thin edge,
just like a chef's knife.

20:20.594 --> 20:22.930
‐ That copper is soft enough

20:22.930 --> 20:24.765
where the blade
can bite into it,

20:24.765 --> 20:25.766
but then grab it.

20:25.766 --> 20:27.852
‐ Once that edge
bites in and digs,

20:27.852 --> 20:29.437
that blade rolls...
‐ Ping!

20:29.437 --> 20:31.605
‐ You're just snapping little
crescent moons out of it.

20:31.605 --> 20:32.773
Not good.

20:32.773 --> 20:34.358
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:34.358 --> 20:35.943
‐ 20 minutes, bladesmiths!

20:35.943 --> 20:38.404
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:38.404 --> 20:41.073
‐ We got a hole!
We have a hole.

20:41.073 --> 20:43.033
It's time to make
some handle magic happen.

20:43.033 --> 20:46.203
Getting it. This blade's sharp.

20:46.203 --> 20:47.913
‐ I think Wayne chose
just about

20:47.913 --> 20:50.916
the worst organic
handle material

20:50.916 --> 20:52.251
you could choose.

20:52.251 --> 20:54.545
‐ It's purpleheart, so it's got
a lot of natural oils in it,

20:54.545 --> 20:57.465
which is what makes it
such a great handle material,

20:57.465 --> 20:59.341
but you gotta take
the time cutting it.

20:59.341 --> 21:00.634
‐ Come on, baby.

21:00.634 --> 21:02.636
‐ You can't shove it
through a metal band saw.

21:02.636 --> 21:04.972
It just turns the glue
on the blade.

21:04.972 --> 21:06.432
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:06.432 --> 21:08.976
‐ [bleep].
The thing jams up on me.

21:08.976 --> 21:11.395
<i>Then my piece of</i>
<i>wood gets stuck.</i>

21:11.395 --> 21:13.981
And it looks like
I broke a tool here.

21:16.066 --> 21:17.234
What am I gonna do now?

21:17.234 --> 21:19.111
<i>Maybe a smaller saw will work,</i>

21:19.111 --> 21:20.696
so I take the small porta band.

21:20.696 --> 21:22.740
Right now, I'm just
fighting the clock

21:22.740 --> 21:24.200
to get this handle done.

21:24.200 --> 21:26.952
‐ Wayne's still gotta put
an edge on that blade,

21:26.952 --> 21:29.580
and he still has
to shape that handle.

21:29.580 --> 21:32.333
‐ Like, I'm just freaking out
now at this point.

21:32.333 --> 21:33.542
<i>I don't know if I'm gonna</i>
<i>get this thing done.</i>

21:33.542 --> 21:35.586
<i>I need to speed up</i>
<i>the process.</i>

21:35.586 --> 21:37.713
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:37.713 --> 21:40.758
‐ I need to attach my scales
to the handle really quick,

21:40.758 --> 21:43.219
and I need to shape them
into a useable shape.

21:43.219 --> 21:45.596
‐ Aaron is working feverishly

21:45.596 --> 21:49.266
to get his handle
glued up to his tang.

21:49.266 --> 21:52.019
<i>‐ As soon as I roughed in</i>
<i>the radiuses on the handle,</i>

21:52.019 --> 21:54.271
<i>I realized that</i>
<i>the time is just ticking</i>

21:54.271 --> 21:57.441
and ticking and ticking,
and it's not waiting for me.

21:57.441 --> 21:59.318
<i>My blade and my handle</i>
<i>are just still</i>

21:59.318 --> 22:00.986
dripping wet with epoxy.

22:00.986 --> 22:03.864
<i>But I need to put an edge</i>
<i>on the blade really quick.</i>

22:03.864 --> 22:06.700
I'm going to put a convex edge
into the blade.

22:06.700 --> 22:09.912
<i>The point here is to have</i>
<i>a sharp enough edge</i>

22:09.912 --> 22:11.580
after the copper tube chop

22:11.580 --> 22:13.499
to cut through a watermelon

22:13.499 --> 22:15.251
instead of smashing
through a watermelon.

22:15.251 --> 22:18.295
‐ Aaron over here, he's gonna
have to hurry this up.

22:18.295 --> 22:20.506
‐ Come on, man.
‐ 30 seconds!

22:20.506 --> 22:22.466
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:22.466 --> 22:25.761
Five, four, three,

22:25.761 --> 22:27.930
two, one.

22:27.930 --> 22:31.183
Bladesmiths,
stop what you're doing.

22:31.183 --> 22:34.186
This second round of
competition is over.

22:34.186 --> 22:35.563
‐ Whoo!

22:35.563 --> 22:38.023
‐ I wish I had more time
to make my handle look pretty,

22:38.023 --> 22:39.984
but, you know what,
it feels good, it looks good.

22:39.984 --> 22:41.110
It'll work.

22:41.110 --> 22:43.904
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to our strength test.

22:43.904 --> 22:47.533
Now, what I'm gonna do is
take each of your choppers

22:47.533 --> 22:49.869
<i>and strike them repeatedly</i>

22:49.869 --> 22:52.079
<i>into these upright</i>
<i>copper pipes.</i>

22:52.079 --> 22:55.040
I don't really care what
your blades do to the pipes.

22:55.040 --> 22:57.293
What I wanna see is what
the pipes do to your blades.

22:57.293 --> 22:59.169
Aaron, you're up first.
How are you feeling?

22:59.169 --> 23:02.172
‐ I'm ready, man.
This is why I'm here.

23:02.172 --> 23:05.301
<i>So, the only thing</i>
<i>more destructive than</i>

23:05.301 --> 23:06.886
<i>smashing a blade</i>
<i>into a copper pipe</i>

23:06.886 --> 23:09.638
is J. Neilson smashing
a blade into a copper pipe.

23:09.638 --> 23:12.641
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:12.641 --> 23:15.561
‐ [grunting]

23:15.561 --> 23:22.735
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:23.736 --> 23:25.863
‐ [exhales]
‐ Well, his piece survived.

23:25.863 --> 23:27.531
Now, we do have
some edge damage here.

23:27.531 --> 23:31.493
You've got some chipping
all up along here in this area,

23:31.493 --> 23:33.829
and I got a chunk out of here.

23:33.829 --> 23:35.789
Overall, you survived.

23:35.789 --> 23:36.999
Good job.
‐ Thanks, J.

23:36.999 --> 23:38.250
‐ How are you
feeling now, Wayne?

23:38.250 --> 23:40.294
‐ Crazy.
‐ Well, let's get crazy.

23:40.294 --> 23:41.754
‐ Let's do it.

23:41.754 --> 23:43.505
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:43.505 --> 23:46.258
<i>So, Aaron took a little</i>
<i>damage, you know,</i>

23:46.258 --> 23:47.635
<i>but it held up</i>
<i>for the most part.</i>

23:47.635 --> 23:49.595
<i>But I'm on pins and needles</i>
<i>right now,</i>

23:49.595 --> 23:51.013
feeling nervous as ever.

23:51.013 --> 23:53.223
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:53.223 --> 23:55.184
‐ [grunts]

23:55.184 --> 23:59.688
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:59.688 --> 24:00.940
‐ [exhales]

24:00.940 --> 24:02.816
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:02.816 --> 24:04.068
‐ Good job, Wayne,
you survived.

24:04.068 --> 24:07.613
Your edge held up.
You don't have any rolling.

24:07.613 --> 24:09.073
Now, as far as your handle,

24:09.073 --> 24:11.033
not great,
but pretty comfortable.

24:11.033 --> 24:12.326
You contoured it enough,

24:12.326 --> 24:15.496
where I knew where
the edge was every time.

24:15.496 --> 24:17.623
Good job.
‐ Thank you.

24:17.623 --> 24:20.542
‐ Okay, Mark, you're up.
‐ Let's do it.

24:20.542 --> 24:21.877
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:21.877 --> 24:24.713
<i>I'm nervous that I didn't</i>
<i>leave my blade stout enough</i>

24:24.713 --> 24:26.382
<i>to not break.</i>

24:26.382 --> 24:29.760
These copper pipes are much
bigger than I was expecting.

24:29.760 --> 24:35.474
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:35.474 --> 24:38.978
‐ [grunting]

24:38.978 --> 24:40.104
[exhales]

24:40.104 --> 24:41.230
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:41.230 --> 24:43.482
‐ All right, Mark, it survived,

24:43.482 --> 24:45.192
but we got a couple issues.

24:45.192 --> 24:47.987
There's a lot of chipping
in the blade here,

24:47.987 --> 24:50.197
and there's a piece of
your steel right there.

24:50.197 --> 24:53.409
Also, your handle could use
a little more indexing,

24:53.409 --> 24:55.536
a little more space here,
a little more width.

24:55.536 --> 24:57.997
You've got some issues,
but you survived.

24:57.997 --> 24:59.748
Good job.
‐ Thank you.

24:59.748 --> 25:02.126
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:02.126 --> 25:03.335
‐ All right, bladesmiths,

25:03.335 --> 25:05.504
this is the sharpness test,
the melon slice.

25:05.504 --> 25:08.716
I'm gonna cut that rope,
and it's gonna drop the melon.

25:10.592 --> 25:12.219
‐ Aaron, you're up first.
You ready?

25:12.219 --> 25:14.722
‐ I'm ready to go.
Let's do it.

25:14.722 --> 25:17.016
<i>My edge wasn't designed</i>
<i>to cut through rope,</i>

25:17.016 --> 25:18.017
<i>so I'm sweating,</i>

25:18.017 --> 25:19.893
and I don't know
how the melon's gonna cut.

25:19.893 --> 25:26.984
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:35.159 --> 25:36.535
‐ All right, Aaron,

25:36.535 --> 25:39.246
the initial cut on the rope
didn't cut all the way through.

25:39.246 --> 25:41.206
The sheer second cut
with slicing,

25:41.206 --> 25:42.916
it cut, released the melon.

25:42.916 --> 25:45.627
Here's the issue:
It crushed the melon.

25:45.627 --> 25:47.880
This part right here,
that you can see right here,

25:47.880 --> 25:49.089
as the slice went through,

25:49.089 --> 25:50.257
that's the part
that cut the melon.

25:50.257 --> 25:53.469
The initial contact
right here crushed it,

25:53.469 --> 25:54.762
and then it sliced it.

25:54.762 --> 25:57.264
But...it'll still cut.

25:57.264 --> 25:58.599
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:58.599 --> 26:00.517
All right, Wayne, you're up.
Are you ready?

26:00.517 --> 26:02.269
‐ Absolutely.
‐ Let's do this.

26:02.269 --> 26:09.359
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:18.285 --> 26:21.955
All right, first up,
your edge is razor sharp.

26:21.955 --> 26:23.540
Easily cut through the rope.

26:23.540 --> 26:25.042
As you can see,
the melon slice,

26:25.042 --> 26:27.628
it's a nice clean line
in the cuts there.

26:27.628 --> 26:30.631
Overall, sir, your weapon,
it will cut.

26:30.631 --> 26:32.132
‐ Yeah!
‐ Good job, Wayne.

26:32.132 --> 26:33.300
‐ Thank you.

26:33.300 --> 26:34.802
‐ All right, Mark,
you're up next. You ready?

26:34.802 --> 26:37.096
‐ Let's do it.
‐ Let's do this.

26:37.096 --> 26:44.103
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:48.148 --> 26:51.568
All right, Mark, your edge
on the rope cut cleanly.

26:51.568 --> 26:53.320
No issues over there.

26:53.320 --> 26:55.030
On the melon slice,

26:55.030 --> 26:56.907
you can see there are
some jagged edges

26:56.907 --> 26:59.910
of where you had some
edge damage right here.

26:59.910 --> 27:01.829
But on the rest of the slice,

27:01.829 --> 27:03.914
it cut cleanly on this
other part right here.

27:03.914 --> 27:05.207
That is sharp.

27:05.207 --> 27:08.210
Overall, sir,
your weapon will cut.

27:08.210 --> 27:09.503
‐ I've been waiting
years to hear that.

27:09.503 --> 27:11.797
Thank you.
‐ [chuckles]

27:11.797 --> 27:12.798
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:12.798 --> 27:14.174
‐ All right, bladesmiths,

27:14.174 --> 27:16.468
only two of you can move
forward into the final.

27:16.468 --> 27:18.220
It's time for one of you
to leave The Forge.

27:18.220 --> 27:20.681
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

27:20.681 --> 27:23.100
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:23.100 --> 27:25.519
Aaron.
Your blade didn't make the cut.

27:25.519 --> 27:28.230
‐ Aaron, the ironic thing is,

27:28.230 --> 27:30.315
all three of us judges
really like

27:30.315 --> 27:32.150
the look and profile
of your blade.

27:32.150 --> 27:34.736
But on the strength test,
it took the most damage,

27:34.736 --> 27:37.531
and it can be seen
in the sharpness test.

27:37.531 --> 27:40.033
It's for those reasons
we're sending you home.

27:40.033 --> 27:42.494
‐ Aaron, please
surrender your blade.

27:42.494 --> 27:43.829
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:43.829 --> 27:46.081
<i>‐ The fact that I made it</i>
<i>as far as I did</i>

27:46.081 --> 27:48.458
is a clear indicator
that I'm on the right track.

27:48.458 --> 27:50.878
Boys!
‐ You did great, man.

27:50.878 --> 27:53.797
<i>‐ To have moved on</i>
<i>from so many passions,</i>

27:53.797 --> 27:57.885
<i>and to have found something</i>
<i>that I'm so motivated to do,</i>

27:57.885 --> 28:00.554
it's a dream come true
in itself.

28:00.554 --> 28:02.764
I'm just honored
to have been here.

28:02.764 --> 28:04.474
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:04.474 --> 28:06.810
‐ Wayne, Mark, congratulations.

28:06.810 --> 28:09.605
You fellas have made it into the
final round of this competition.

28:09.605 --> 28:11.356
Now we're sending you
back to your home forges

28:11.356 --> 28:13.775
to recreate
an iconic weapon from history.

28:13.775 --> 28:16.778
And that weapon is...
‐ Show me a falchion.

28:16.778 --> 28:18.697
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:18.697 --> 28:20.240
‐ A falchion.

28:20.240 --> 28:22.367
‐ Yeah.
‐ Ah‐ha‐ha, yeah!

28:22.367 --> 28:24.119
<i>‐ One of</i>
<i>the most popular weapons</i>

28:24.119 --> 28:25.245
<i>during the Middle Ages,</i>

28:25.245 --> 28:26.914
<i>the falchion was</i>
<i>a commoner's sword</i>

28:26.914 --> 28:28.206
<i>that found widespread use</i>

28:28.206 --> 28:30.709
<i>both on and off</i>
<i>European battlefields.</i>

28:30.709 --> 28:31.877
<i>A thick and heavy sword,</i>

28:31.877 --> 28:33.879
<i>falchions featured</i>
<i>either a straight</i>

28:33.879 --> 28:36.381
<i>or slightly curved blade</i>
<i>with a single‐sharp edge,</i>

28:36.381 --> 28:38.300
<i>making it well‐suited</i>
<i>for the vicious,</i>

28:38.300 --> 28:40.594
<i>close quarters combat</i>
<i>of medieval wars.</i>

28:40.594 --> 28:43.305
<i>Eventually, this broad</i>
<i>and deadly hacking weapon</i>

28:43.305 --> 28:46.308
<i>transitioned from a combat</i>
<i>sidearm to a hunting sword,</i>

28:46.308 --> 28:48.936
<i>like other historic</i>
<i>European weapons of its time.</i>

28:48.936 --> 28:50.395
<i>Although the falcion</i>
<i>disappeared</i>

28:50.395 --> 28:52.105
<i>from battlefields</i>
<i>and hunting grounds,</i>

28:52.105 --> 28:54.983
<i>its legacy virtually lives on</i>
<i>in video games,</i>

28:54.983 --> 28:58.820
<i>like "Warhammer: Vermintide 2"</i>
<i>and "Dark Souls 3."</i>

28:58.820 --> 29:01.448
<i>‐ I have never made</i>
<i>a sword this big before,</i>

29:01.448 --> 29:05.327
so this is new territory for me,
but let's see what I can do.

29:05.327 --> 29:07.454
‐ Gentlemen, in this final
round of competition,

29:07.454 --> 29:09.122
you'll have to forge a falchion,

29:09.122 --> 29:10.874
and it must fall within
the following parameters:

29:10.874 --> 29:12.250
The length of the blade

29:12.250 --> 29:14.920
must be between
25 and 27 inches in length.

29:14.920 --> 29:17.130
The width of the blade
at the base must be 2 inches,

29:17.130 --> 29:20.968
and flair to at least
3 1/4 inches towards the tip.

29:20.968 --> 29:22.302
It's single‐edged, gentlemen.

29:22.302 --> 29:26.682
You must include a disk pommel
and a cruciform upswept guard.

29:26.682 --> 29:28.976
For this round, we'll be
kicking it up a notch.

29:28.976 --> 29:31.144
You will have only four days
at your home forges

29:31.144 --> 29:32.771
in which to complete your work.

29:32.771 --> 29:34.314
At the end of those four days,

29:34.314 --> 29:36.108
you'll return and present
your falchions

29:36.108 --> 29:37.734
to our panel of expert judges,

29:37.734 --> 29:39.486
and after they've
thoroughly tested them,

29:39.486 --> 29:41.613
they'll declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

29:41.613 --> 29:45.409
who walks out of this forge
with a check for $10,000.

29:45.409 --> 29:47.828
Good luck.
We'll see you in four days.

29:47.828 --> 29:50.872
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:50.872 --> 29:52.040
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:52.040 --> 29:53.500
<i>‐ We made it back.</i>

29:53.500 --> 29:55.210
Welcome to Pirate Forge.

29:55.210 --> 29:58.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:58.130 --> 30:00.841
<i>Now, I've done my research,</i>
<i>and back in the day,</i>

30:00.841 --> 30:03.677
the armor was getting tougher,
you know, thicker leather,

30:03.677 --> 30:05.554
the introduction of chainmail
and whatnot.

30:05.554 --> 30:07.305
<i>So, they needed something</i>
<i>that was gonna cut</i>

30:07.305 --> 30:09.224
<i>and chop with</i>
<i>the strength of an axe,</i>

30:09.224 --> 30:11.101
<i>but still be welded</i>
<i>like a sword,</i>

30:11.101 --> 30:13.103
and that's when
the falchion was born.

30:13.103 --> 30:15.022
<i>My plan</i>
<i>for the design on this,</i>

30:15.022 --> 30:16.523
I'm gonna go with
the Damascus pattern.

30:16.523 --> 30:18.108
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:18.108 --> 30:20.652
What I wanna do is just
make two solid billets

30:20.652 --> 30:22.863
that we draw out,
cut, and restack,

30:22.863 --> 30:25.532
<i>to make the one billet</i>
<i>for the falchion.</i>

30:25.532 --> 30:26.783
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:26.783 --> 30:28.368
<i>This is really taking</i>
<i>a lot of time.</i>

30:28.368 --> 30:29.870
I mean, this is a lot more work

30:29.870 --> 30:31.163
than I thought
it was going to be.

30:31.163 --> 30:33.165
<i>Hammering out and</i>
<i>setting forge welds</i>

30:33.165 --> 30:34.583
<i>on such monster billets,</i>

30:34.583 --> 30:36.209
I've definitely forgot,

30:36.209 --> 30:38.211
you know,
how difficult that was.

30:38.211 --> 30:40.714
I mean, if I would've used
a monosteel billet,

30:40.714 --> 30:42.758
I could've already had
this falchion forged.

30:42.758 --> 30:44.384
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:44.384 --> 30:46.386
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:46.386 --> 30:47.637
<i>‐ We're here back</i>
<i>in my home forge</i>

30:47.637 --> 30:49.014
<i>in South Burlington, Vermont.</i>

30:49.014 --> 30:50.307
Boom.

30:50.307 --> 30:52.893
I think that four days is tight.

30:52.893 --> 30:54.061
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:54.061 --> 30:56.354
Man, a 3/8‐inch is no joke.

30:56.354 --> 30:58.231
The falchion has this swell

30:58.231 --> 31:00.067
<i>that really gives</i>
<i>a lot of forward weight</i>

31:00.067 --> 31:01.526
<i>that makes it great</i>
<i>for chopping.</i>

31:01.526 --> 31:05.655
<i>So, I have to figure out where</i>
<i>I wanna put in this swell</i>

31:05.655 --> 31:07.240
and how to hammer it out.

31:07.240 --> 31:08.408
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:08.408 --> 31:10.744
It's so thin.
[sighs]

31:10.744 --> 31:14.790
I'm pretty convinced that this
first swell that I've created,

31:14.790 --> 31:17.167
<i>I've just hammered</i>
<i>incorrectly.</i>

31:17.167 --> 31:19.419
I'm gonna try my hardest
to get this to work,

31:19.419 --> 31:21.463
and if I can't get it to 3 1/4

31:21.463 --> 31:23.590
<i>without compromising</i>
<i>the structural integrity,</i>

31:23.590 --> 31:25.383
I have to start over tomorrow.

31:25.383 --> 31:27.052
<i>If I have to start over,</i>

31:27.052 --> 31:29.429
that means that I've
wasted an entire day.

31:29.429 --> 31:31.181
[sighs]

31:31.181 --> 31:32.390
[bleep].

31:35.268 --> 31:36.686
‐ It's so thin.
<i>[m</i>

31:36.686 --> 31:37.854
[sighs]

31:37.854 --> 31:40.273
I finally get
this swell drawn out,

31:40.273 --> 31:43.068
and it is just way too thin.

31:43.068 --> 31:44.528
<i>And I'm not even close</i>
<i>to 3 inches.</i>

31:44.528 --> 31:46.738
I'm pretty nervous about
the structural stability

31:46.738 --> 31:48.073
of what I'm making...

31:48.073 --> 31:49.074
Ugh.

31:49.074 --> 31:51.535
So I am just gonna start
on a second swell.

31:51.535 --> 31:53.120
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:53.120 --> 31:55.038
I'm giving up on this flair,

31:55.038 --> 31:57.207
because it's just too thin,

31:57.207 --> 32:00.043
and I still have
enough metal back here

32:00.043 --> 32:01.461
<i>to make it work.</i>

32:01.461 --> 32:03.046
<i>What I realized is</i>
<i>that the first time,</i>

32:03.046 --> 32:05.590
I wanted to move the metal
completely horizontally,

32:05.590 --> 32:06.925
from spine to edge,

32:06.925 --> 32:09.052
<i>and the way that I was</i>
<i>doing it was moving</i>

32:09.052 --> 32:10.929
<i>some of the metal length‐wise,</i>

32:10.929 --> 32:12.639
and enough of the
metal length‐wise

32:12.639 --> 32:14.766
that it just got too thin.

32:14.766 --> 32:16.268
<i>I put into practice</i>

32:16.268 --> 32:17.936
<i>what I learned making</i>
<i>the first swell.</i>

32:17.936 --> 32:21.731
It's already going
a lot better, a lot faster,

32:21.731 --> 32:22.983
and getting a lot wider,

32:22.983 --> 32:26.236
<i>without getting as thin</i>
<i>as it did the first time.</i>

32:26.236 --> 32:27.946
That's it for day one.

32:27.946 --> 32:30.073
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:30.073 --> 32:31.366
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:31.366 --> 32:33.076
<i>‐ It's day two.</i>
<i>The best‐case scenario:</i>

32:33.076 --> 32:34.995
<i>We get this sucker drawn out,</i>
<i>we get it quenched,</i>

32:34.995 --> 32:36.288
it comes out looking great.

32:36.288 --> 32:37.914
<i>Never quenched</i>
<i>a blade this big.</i>

32:37.914 --> 32:39.958
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>what's going to happen.</i>

32:39.958 --> 32:42.627
About to make this thing
change into a real sword.

32:42.627 --> 32:44.754
This is a special,
momentous occasion.

32:44.754 --> 32:47.757
<i>I was so inspired</i>
<i>by this blade,</i>

32:47.757 --> 32:50.218
I was like, "There should
be a falchion song."

32:50.218 --> 32:53.221
[acoustic guitar playing]

32:53.221 --> 32:54.806
♪ ♪

32:54.806 --> 32:59.186
♪ Oh, it was born
of blood and war ♪

32:59.186 --> 33:00.604
♪ ♪

33:00.604 --> 33:04.983
<i>♪ Half axe and half sword ♪</i>

33:04.983 --> 33:09.112
♪ It would surely
lop off your head ♪

33:09.112 --> 33:10.155
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:10.155 --> 33:14.784
♪ I just made me a falchion ♪

33:14.784 --> 33:15.952
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:15.952 --> 33:18.455
There she is.
A blade has been born!

33:18.455 --> 33:21.666
That blade came out
super straight as an arrow.

33:21.666 --> 33:22.876
<i>Fantastic.</i>

33:22.876 --> 33:25.170
Looks like those candles
and all the stuff we did

33:25.170 --> 33:26.546
sure enough worked.

33:26.546 --> 33:29.591
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:29.591 --> 33:30.967
‐ The morning of day two,

33:30.967 --> 33:33.136
and I'm gonna start
on my cross guard.

33:33.136 --> 33:36.473
I only have one piece of brass
that I can try this with,

33:36.473 --> 33:38.850
so I'm hoping to get it
right on the first try.

33:38.850 --> 33:40.602
<i>The fittings are</i>
<i>a huge part of this,</i>

33:40.602 --> 33:44.397
and getting all of that to just
really fit tightly, snuggly,

33:44.397 --> 33:47.192
be comfortable in the hand,
is gonna be, hopefully,

33:47.192 --> 33:49.069
where I'm able
to win this competition.

33:49.069 --> 33:50.987
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:50.987 --> 33:52.656
Should be good enough.

33:52.656 --> 33:54.115
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:54.115 --> 33:56.034
‐ Let's do this!

33:56.034 --> 33:58.119
I'm feeling good about the blade
going into the last day.

33:58.119 --> 33:59.496
<i>My only concern is just</i>

33:59.496 --> 34:00.997
<i>getting the weight</i>
<i>where it needs to be.</i>

34:00.997 --> 34:02.207
It's a little bit heavy.

34:02.207 --> 34:04.668
I've went ahead and decided,
we're going for fullers.

34:04.668 --> 34:07.671
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:07.671 --> 34:09.381
<i>I don't have</i>
<i>a whole lot of time left.</i>

34:09.381 --> 34:11.049
<i>I am gonna have to</i>
<i>be very strategic</i>

34:11.049 --> 34:13.218
in everything I do today.

34:13.218 --> 34:14.886
<i>I feel so accomplished.</i>

34:14.886 --> 34:18.682
You know, for four days,
pulling off a blade this big,

34:18.682 --> 34:20.016
<i>with the Damascus pattern,</i>

34:20.016 --> 34:21.810
<i>with the fit and finish</i>
<i>that I got on it.</i>

34:21.810 --> 34:23.186
I couldn't be any happier.

34:23.186 --> 34:26.690
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:26.690 --> 34:28.358
‐ It's the dawn
of the final day.

34:28.358 --> 34:30.568
<i>I was able to get the blade</i>
<i>quenched and tempered.</i>

34:30.568 --> 34:31.861
Perfect.

34:31.861 --> 34:35.699
Now it's time to grind,
shape, and glue.

34:35.699 --> 34:37.200
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:37.200 --> 34:39.661
This has been a bunch
of firsts for me:

34:39.661 --> 34:42.706
first on length,
first on a guard,

34:42.706 --> 34:43.915
<i>first on a pommel.</i>

34:43.915 --> 34:45.709
It is just non‐stop firsts.

34:45.709 --> 34:48.461
<i>I know that there are</i>
<i>some steps that I rushed,</i>

34:48.461 --> 34:51.423
but for a four‐day build,
I'm pretty happy with this.

34:51.423 --> 34:55.260
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:55.260 --> 34:56.678
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome back to The Forge.

34:56.678 --> 34:58.263
You've had four days
at your home forges

34:58.263 --> 35:00.223
to work on your finale weapons.

35:00.223 --> 35:01.683
Wayne, how'd it go?

35:01.683 --> 35:03.101
<i>‐ It went great.</i>

35:03.101 --> 35:06.271
<i>I used alternating layers</i>
<i>of 15N20 and 1095</i>

35:06.271 --> 35:08.273
<i>to pull off</i>
<i>a 200‐layer falchion.</i>

35:08.273 --> 35:11.443
<i>A hand‐forged</i>
<i>mild steel guard,</i>

35:11.443 --> 35:13.278
<i>hickory and leather stack</i>
<i>on the handle,</i>

35:13.278 --> 35:14.613
<i>and then a mild steel pommel.</i>

35:14.613 --> 35:17.574
‐ All right.
Mark, what do you think?

35:17.574 --> 35:19.075
‐ This is absolutely exhausting.

35:19.075 --> 35:20.368
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:20.368 --> 35:23.204
<i>So, I made a falchion</i>
<i>out of 80CRV2,</i>

35:23.204 --> 35:26.458
<i>used walnut for the handle</i>
<i>and brass and fittings.</i>

35:26.458 --> 35:27.917
‐ All right, gents,
well, now it's time to see

35:27.917 --> 35:31.296
if those weapons work
as nicely as you look.

35:31.296 --> 35:32.589
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:32.589 --> 35:34.799
There will be a strength test,
a sharpness test,

35:34.799 --> 35:36.301
and a KEAL test.
Doug?

35:36.301 --> 35:38.094
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:38.094 --> 35:41.931
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
this is the KEAL test.

35:41.931 --> 35:43.475
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:43.475 --> 35:46.019
To find out what kinda lethal
damage your weapon will do

35:46.019 --> 35:47.562
according to
its historic design,

35:47.562 --> 35:50.357
I will try to cut
this pig carcass in half.

35:50.357 --> 35:52.108
Wayne, you're up first.
You ready for this?

35:52.108 --> 35:54.444
‐ Absolutely.
‐ Let's do this.

35:54.444 --> 35:56.571
<i>‐ I'm feeling</i>
<i>excited and nervous</i>

35:56.571 --> 35:57.822
<i>all at the same time.</i>

35:57.822 --> 36:01.117
It's a tough test, 'cause
you got a big, monster hog.

36:01.117 --> 36:06.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:06.748 --> 36:08.667
‐ [chuckles] Oh, man.
‐ Nice.

36:08.667 --> 36:10.627
‐ One and done.
‐ Well, now.

36:10.627 --> 36:14.297
‐ All right, Wayne,
your falchion is beautiful.

36:14.297 --> 36:15.799
It is sharp.

36:15.799 --> 36:17.842
It cut through the spine and
all the way through the pig.

36:17.842 --> 36:21.137
It's a little bit heavier
for a one‐handed weapon,

36:21.137 --> 36:22.722
but it is well‐balanced.

36:22.722 --> 36:25.016
Overall, sir, it will KEAL.

36:25.016 --> 36:26.976
‐ [chuckles]
Awesome.

36:26.976 --> 36:29.396
‐ All right, Mark,
your turn, sir.

36:30.730 --> 36:33.108
‐ Are you ready?
‐ Let's give it a shot.
Are you ready?
‐ Let's give it a shot.

36:33.108 --> 36:34.651
<i>Wayne set the bar really high</i>

36:34.651 --> 36:36.861
by cutting the pig
in half in one hit,

36:36.861 --> 36:38.738
<i>so I'm nervous.</i>

36:38.738 --> 36:41.700
<i>The best I can do is to hope</i>
<i>for the same performance.</i>

36:41.700 --> 36:48.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:55.922 --> 36:58.591
‐ All right, Mark, let's talk
about your falchion here.

36:58.591 --> 37:00.552
It's a nice, lighter blade.

37:00.552 --> 37:03.763
Your edges are sharp enough
to cut through spine.

37:03.763 --> 37:05.932
But the problem I have
here is your guard.

37:05.932 --> 37:08.893
Your edges here are not rounded.

37:08.893 --> 37:11.771
They dig in right here
where the thumb is.

37:11.771 --> 37:15.150
But your blade, sir,
it will KEAL.

37:15.150 --> 37:16.151
‐ Thank you.

37:16.151 --> 37:17.277
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:17.277 --> 37:19.154
‐ All right, gentlemen,
to test the strength

37:19.154 --> 37:20.739
and overall construction
of your blades,

37:20.739 --> 37:24.117
I'll be attacking
our armored dummy here.

37:24.117 --> 37:27.871
This test is not about what
your swords do to that armor.

37:27.871 --> 37:30.081
It's about what that armor
does to your swords.

37:30.081 --> 37:32.083
Wayne, you're up.
Are you ready?

37:32.083 --> 37:33.501
‐ Let's do it.

37:33.501 --> 37:40.550
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:50.185 --> 37:52.645
Whoo.
[chuckles]

37:52.645 --> 37:54.022
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:54.022 --> 37:55.982
‐ First off, Wayne,
your edge has taken

37:55.982 --> 37:58.943
some small chips,
some small rolls.

37:58.943 --> 38:00.820
But it's very,
very minor damage.

38:00.820 --> 38:02.363
There's still a sharp edge here.

38:02.363 --> 38:03.740
All in all,
it held up beautifully.

38:03.740 --> 38:05.366
‐ All right, thank you.

38:05.366 --> 38:08.036
‐ So, Mark, I gotta ask,
what's with the shirt?

38:08.036 --> 38:09.662
‐ I got married
in this shirt, actually.

38:09.662 --> 38:12.040
Uh, it's, you know‐‐
it's my formal wear.

38:12.040 --> 38:14.042
‐ All right, well,
are you ready for the test?

38:14.042 --> 38:16.211
‐ I am.
‐ Okay.

38:16.211 --> 38:23.301
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:33.394 --> 38:35.188
‐ Not bad.

38:35.188 --> 38:36.940
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:36.940 --> 38:40.360
‐ All right, so, first off,
the blade is still solid.

38:40.360 --> 38:42.278
It did get some minor rolling,

38:42.278 --> 38:44.697
but the blade
still has an edge.

38:44.697 --> 38:45.740
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:45.740 --> 38:46.991
Down here is the problem.

38:46.991 --> 38:49.828
Your guard, these edges
are not just square,

38:49.828 --> 38:51.371
they're sharp.

38:51.371 --> 38:52.872
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:52.872 --> 38:54.666
But the blade held up.

38:54.666 --> 38:56.209
Good job.
‐ Thank you.

38:56.209 --> 38:58.795
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:58.795 --> 39:01.047
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
now it's time to find out

39:01.047 --> 39:03.216
if there's any sharpness
left to your weapons.

39:03.216 --> 39:05.051
To test the edge of your weapon,

39:05.051 --> 39:07.512
I'm gonna cut through
this gauntlet of sandbags.

39:07.512 --> 39:09.055
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:09.055 --> 39:10.723
Wayne, you're up first.
Are you ready for this?

39:10.723 --> 39:11.891
‐ Oh, yeah.

39:11.891 --> 39:18.982
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:34.539 --> 39:37.542
‐ All right, Wayne,
your weapon is sharp.

39:37.542 --> 39:40.962
On every swing,
it cuts and slashes nicely.

39:40.962 --> 39:42.589
And most importantly,

39:42.589 --> 39:46.259
aside from being smurf'd,
it will cut.

39:46.259 --> 39:47.594
‐ Awesome.

39:47.594 --> 39:48.678
‐ All right, Mark,
it's your turn.

39:48.678 --> 39:50.013
You ready?
‐ I am.

39:50.013 --> 39:51.598
‐ Let's have fun.

39:51.598 --> 39:58.730
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:08.072 --> 40:09.824
All right, Mark,
as you can see,

40:09.824 --> 40:12.160
on both of these bags,
it cut deeply.

40:12.160 --> 40:14.370
On the second bag,
on the swing back over there,

40:14.370 --> 40:16.122
<i>it must have hit a dull spot.</i>

40:16.122 --> 40:18.082
It did rip parts of the bag,

40:18.082 --> 40:19.709
but it didn't cut
all the way in.

40:19.709 --> 40:22.879
But, overall, it is sharp,
and it will cut.

40:22.879 --> 40:24.631
‐ Thank you.

40:24.631 --> 40:28.635
‐ Wayne, Mark,
it was a tight decision.

40:28.635 --> 40:31.512
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:31.512 --> 40:34.807
Wayne, congratulations, you're
the "Forged in Fire" champion.

40:34.807 --> 40:38.311
Mark, unfortunately,
your blade didn't make the cut.

40:38.311 --> 40:40.730
‐ Mark, you made a good blade.
There's no doubt about that.

40:40.730 --> 40:42.774
But the big problem is
mainly your guard.

40:42.774 --> 40:44.609
Not rounding those sections,

40:44.609 --> 40:47.403
those sharp corners will bite
into the user's hand,

40:47.403 --> 40:49.280
and if a weapon's
gonna hurt a user,

40:49.280 --> 40:51.532
they're not gonna use it.

40:51.532 --> 40:54.118
‐ Please surrender your weapon
and leave The Forge.

40:54.118 --> 40:56.120
<i>‐ From start to finish,</i>

40:56.120 --> 40:58.331
<i>this whole thing was</i>
<i>a learning process for me,</i>

40:58.331 --> 41:00.166
<i>and I honestly think</i>
<i>I have gotten</i>

41:00.166 --> 41:03.336
years worth of experience
and feedback

41:03.336 --> 41:05.129
in just a short time.

41:05.129 --> 41:06.881
Great job, man.
‐ Yeah, you too.

41:06.881 --> 41:09.842
‐ This experience
was life‐changing.

41:09.842 --> 41:12.637
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:12.637 --> 41:14.847
‐ Wayne, congratulations.

41:14.847 --> 41:18.351
You are one bad‐ass
everlasting bladesmith,

41:18.351 --> 41:20.603
and our new
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:20.603 --> 41:21.688
Good job, brother
[applause]

41:21.688 --> 41:25.066
‐ Yeah! Yes! Yeah!
‐ [laughs]

41:25.066 --> 41:26.484
Please, at this time,

41:26.484 --> 41:29.195
present your blade
to our judges.

41:29.195 --> 41:31.614
‐ So, I did it.
Man, I wanted it.

41:31.614 --> 41:34.200
<i>Next for me, I'm gonna</i>
<i>get back on the same thing</i>

41:34.200 --> 41:35.410
that's led me to this point,

41:35.410 --> 41:38.329
which is just non‐stop,
going full throttle.

41:38.329 --> 41:39.998
<i>I'm just going</i>
<i>to keep pushing.</i>

41:39.998 --> 41:41.833
I'm gonna keep getting
better and better.

41:41.833 --> 41:46.671
